```

---

## Camera state and particles

```js
const camera = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };
const targetCamera = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };

const streamParticles = [];
let tick = 0;
```

---

# Deobfuscated functions

## 1. Find node by ID

The function `a0_0xbe6040` is mostly junk-obfuscation, but the real behavior is:

```js
function getNodeById(id) {
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    if (nodes[i].id === id) return nodes[i];
  }
  return null;
}
```

---

## 2. Physics step for nodes

`a0_0x2c614d()` updates node positions.

### What it does

### A. Repel every node from every other node

For every pair of nodes:

```js
dx = n1.x - n2.x;
dy = n1.y - n2.y;
dist = sqrt(dx*dx + dy*dy) || 1;

force = config.attraction / (dist * dist); // inverse-square force
fx = dx / dist * force;
fy = dy / dist * force;

n1.vx += fx;
n1.vy += fy;
n2.vx -= fx;
n2.vy -= fy;
```

Despite the name `attraction`, this is actually being used as **repulsion**, since each node is pushed away from the other.

---

### B. Apply spring forces for linked nodes

For every link:

```js
const na = getNodeById(link.a);
const nb = getNodeById(link.b);
if (!na || !nb) continue;

dx = nb.x - na.x;
dy = nb.y - na.y;
dist = sqrt(dx*dx + dy*dy) || 1;

stretch = dist - link.rest;
force = (link.k || config.amplification) * stretch;

na.vx += dx / dist * force;
na.vy += dy / dist * force;
nb.vx -= dx / dist * force;
nb.vy -= dy / dist * force;
```

This behaves like springs trying to keep connected nodes near their `rest` distance.

---

### C. Pull all nodes gently back toward center

Center is fixed at `(400, 300)`:

```js
node.vx += (400 - node.x) * config.dispersal;
node.vy += (300 - node.y) * config.dispersal;
```

This prevents the graph from drifting away forever.

---

### D. Damping and integration

```js
node.vx *= config.amplification; // 0.92
node.vy *= config.amplification;
node.x += node.vx;
node.y += node.vy;
```

So nodes keep momentum, but gradually lose energy.

---

## 3. Emit one stream particle

`a0_0x901008()`:

```js
function emitParticle() {
  if (streamParticles.length >= config.streamMax) return;

  const node = nodes[Math.floor(Math.random() * nodes.length)];
  const angle = Math.random() * TAU;
  const speed = 0.3 + Math.random() * INV_SQRT2;

  streamParticles.push({
    x: node.x,
    y: node.y,
    vx: Math.cos(angle) * speed,
    vy: Math.sin(angle) * speed,
    age: 0,
    maxAge: 800 + Math.random() * 1200,
    size: 0.8 + (Math.random() * PHI + INV_SQRT2)
  });
}
```

So every few ticks it spawns a particle at a random node with a random direction and speed.

---

## 4. Update particles

`a0_0x56b204()`:

```js
function updateParticles() {
  for (let i = streamParticles.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    const p = streamParticles[i];

    p.vx *= (1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125);
    p.vy *= (1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125);

    p.x += p.vx;
    p.y += p.vy;
    p.age++;

    if (p.age > p.maxAge) {
      streamParticles.splice(i, 1);
    }
  }
}
```

Particles slowly lose velocity, move, age, and eventually get deleted.

---

## 5. Smooth camera interpolation

`a0_0xb7ed56()`:

```js
function updateCamera() {
  camera.x += (targetCamera.x - camera.x) * config.theta;
  camera.y += (targetCamera.y - camera.y) * config.theta;
  camera.zoom += (targetCamera.zoom - camera.zoom) * config.theta;
}
```

This is a standard easing/smoothing step.

---

## 6. Main tick

`a0_0x2a742c()`:

```js
function tickStep() {
  updateNodePhysics();
  updateParticles();
  updateCamera();

  if (tick % 3 === 0) emitParticle();

  tick++;
}
```

And then:

```js
setInterval(tickStep, 16);
```

So it runs about **60 times per second**.

